documentation.title: Queues documentation
documentation.header: These are FIFO (First In First Out) queues in which batch job execution requests will wait.
documentation.description: On this page, one may change the characteristics of queues. Changes on this page do not require node reboots.

hints.name: The name of the queue. This name is very important, as it the key used to designate the queue in the different APIs (for example, when submitting an execution request, one may specify by name a queue in which the request will wait). However, it can still be changed - internally, JQM uses an ID, not this name - the impact is only on the clients' side.
hints.description: A free text description that appears in reports
hints.isDefault: The queue used when none is specified. There can only be one default queue.

createQueueDialog.title: Create queue
createQueueDialog.defaultQueueLabel: Default queue (disabled if one is already set)

messages.onlyOneDefault: Only one default queue can be set

documentation.title: JNDI Resources documentation
documentation.header: Resources are Java objects which can be requested by jobs through a JNDI lookup.
documentation.description1: On this page, one may create or change resources. Creating a new resource does not require any reboot. Altering an already used singleton resource does require rebooting the nodes using it, as singleton resources are cached. Altering a non-singleton resource does not require any reboot.
documentation.description2: Please note that for a non-singleton resource, its class and factory class must be accessible to the payload: either in JQM_ROOT/ext or inside the payload's own dependencies. For a singleton resource, the classes must be inside ext (as they must be available to the engine itself, not only to the payload).

hints.jndiAlias: The name that will be used by payloads during resource lookup.
hints.type: The fully qualified name of the resource class. E.g. java.io.File.File
hints.factory: The fully qualified name of the resource factory class. E.g. com.enioka.jqm.providers.FileFactory
hints.description: Free text to remember what the resource is for.
hints.singleton: Tick for singleton resource. Differing from standard JNDI resource, a lookup on a singleton resource will always return the same instance (standard JNDI is: a new instance is created on each lookup). This is most helpful for connection pools, for which it is stupid to create a new instance on each call..

documentation.title: Mappings documentation
documentation.header: Mappings specify which nodes will poll which queues. They are basically nodes subscribing to queues.
documentation.description: On this page, one may associate nodes with queues. Running nodes will (by default) check every minute if there are changes in their mappings.

hints.node: The node which will poll the queue
hints.pollingInterval: The polling interval, in milliseconds. Never go below one second. If updated on an active engine, it is applied to the next loop (not the current one).
hints.maxConcurrentInstances: The maximum number of parallel executions the node will allow for this queue (this translates directly as a max number of threads inside the engine).

hints.name: Name of the role. Must be unique.

hints.name: The key used to identify the class loader in the deployment descriptor. Unique.
hints.childFirst: Offer option to have child first class loading. Parent first is the norm in JSE.
hints.hiddenClasses: Offer possibility to hide Java classes from jobs. One or more regex defining classes never to load from the parent class loader.
hints.tracingEnabled: Activate listing all class loaded inside the job log
hints.persistent: When false, the class loader is transient: it is created to run a new job instance and is thrown out when the job instance ends. When true, it is not thrown out at the end and will be reused by all job instances created from the different job definitions using this class loader (therefore, multiple job definitions can share the same static context).
hints.allowedRunners: The different runners that are active in this context. If not set, the global parameter job_runners is used instead.

editHiddenClassesDialog.title: Edit hidden classes
editHiddenClassesDialog.description: A hidden class is a regexp defining classes never to load from the parent class loader.

hints.key: The parameter key. Not necessarily unique.

documentation.title: Cluster-wide parameters documentation
documentation.header: These parameters apply to every node inside the cluster.
documentation.description: On this page, one may change the global cluster parameters. Please see the full documentation for the parameters. The need to reboot after a change depends on the parameter.

hints.name: The name of the node inside the JQM cluster. It has no link whatsoever to hostname, DNS names and whatnot. It is simply the name given as a parameter to the node when starting. It is unique throughout the cluster. Default is server hostname in Windows, user name in Unix.
hints.dns: The web APIs will bind on all interfaces that answer to a reverse DNS call of this name. Default is localhost, i.e. local-only binding.
hints.httpPort: The web APIs will bind on this port. Default is a random free port.
hints.outputDirectory: Should batch jobs produce files, they would be stored in sub-directories of this directory. Absolute path strongly recommended, relative path are relative to JQM install directory.
hints.jobRepoDirectory: The root directory containing all the jobs (payload jars). Absolute path strongly recommended, relative path are relative to JQM install directory.
hints.rootLogLevel: Verbosity of the main log file. Valid values are TRACE, DEBUG, INFO, WARN, ERROR, FATAL. See full documentation for the signification of these levels. In case of erroneous value, default value INFO is assumed.
hints.jmxRegistryPort: If 0, remote JMX is disabled. Default is 0.
hints.jmxServerPort: If 0, remote JMX is disabled. Default is 0.
hints.simpleApi: If ticked, the simple web API will start. This API governs script interactions (execution request through wget & co, etc.) and file retrieval (logs, files created by batch jobs executions)
hints.clientApi: If ticked, the client web API will start. This API exposes the full JqmClient API - see full documentation.
hints.adminApi: If ticked, the administration web API will start. This API is only used by this web administration console and is an internal JQM API, not a public one. Disabling it disables this web console.

documentation.title: Nodes documentation
documentation.header: Nodes are instances of the JQM engine that actually run batch job instances. Basically, they are Unix init.d entries, Windows services or running containers.
documentation.paragraph1: On this page, one may change the characteristics of nodes.
documentation.paragraph2: Nodes can only be created through the command line
documentation.paragraph2End: . Only nodes switched off for more than 10 minutes can be removed.
documentation.paragraph3End: (two asterisks) while the node is running requires the node to be restarted for the change to be taken into account. Changes to other fields are automatically applied asynchronously (default is at most after one minute).

hints.applicationName: The key used to designate the Job Definition in the different APIs and dialogs
hints.description: A human-readable description of what the job does
hints.defaultQueue: The queue which will be used when submitting execution requests (if no specific queue is given at request time)
hints.enabled: If disabled, all instances will always succeed instantly
hints.highlander: If checked, there can never be more than one instance of the Job Definition running at the same time, as well as no more than one waiting in any queue
hints.properties: Specific properties depending on the job type
hints.tags: Optionnal tags for classification and queries

editPropertiesDialog.pathToJarHelper: The relative path to the jar containing the class to run. It is relative to the 'directory containing jars' parameter of the different nodes.
editPropertiesDialog.classToLaunchHelper: The fully qualified name of the class to run. (it must either have a main function, or implement Runnable, or inherit from JobBase).
editPropertiesDialog.classLoaderHelper: The class loader used by the job.
editPropertiesDialog.pathToExecutableHelper: Current path is node job directory. Do not add parameters here, just a path. Process is launched with the value of the provided parameters, sorted by key. Key is only used for sorting.
editPropertiesDialog.shellHelper: Default shell is /bin/sh or cmd.exe. Powershell is Powershell core under Linux and full under Windows.
editPropertiesDialog.shellCommandHelper: Current path is node job directory. JQM environment variables (and others) may be used. 1000 max (988 remaining).
